Predict The Flight Ticket Price Hackathon¶

Flight ticket prices can be something hard to guess, today we might see a price, check out the price of the same flight tomorrow, it will be a different story. We might have often heard travellers saying that flight ticket prices are so unpredictable. Huh! Here we take on the challenge! As data scientists, we are gonna prove that given the right data anything can be predicted. Here you will be provided with prices of flight tickets for various airlines between the months of March and June of 2019 and between various cities. Size of training set: 10683 records Size of test set: 2671 records FEATURES:

  • Airline: The name of the airline.
  • Date_of_Journey: The date of the journey.
  • Source: The source from which the service begins.
  • Destination: The destination where the service ends.
  • Route: The route taken by the flight to reach the destination.
  • Dep_Time: The time when the journey starts from the source.
  • Arrival_Time: Time of arrival at the destination.
  • Duration: Total duration of the flight.
  • Total_Stops: Total stops between the source and destination.
  • Additional_Info: Additional information about the flight.
  • Price: The price of the ticket - TARGET

Goal¶

Creating a machine learning for predicting flight ticket price with high accuracy.

Converting Duration to int value (minutes)¶
In [19]:
ddata = list(map(lambda x: x.split(), data['Duration'].values))
duration_data = []
for i in ddata:
    length = len(i)
    val = int(i[0][:-1]) * 60
    if(length == 2):
        val+= int(i[1][:-1])
    duration_data.append(val)
data['Duration'] = duration_data

del ddata, duration_data, i, val, length
Getting distance travelled for each flight via web scraping on prokerela.com¶
In [20]:
####################################Path#######################################
route = [(list(map(lambda x:x.strip(), i.split('')))) for i in data['Route'].values]
x = set()
for i in route: 
    for j in i: 
        x.add(j)
airports = list(x)
airports_combinations = []
for i in combinations(airports, 2):
    airports_combinations.append(i)

del x, airports
In [21]:
try:
    with open('data/distances.pkl', 'rb') as file:
        distances = pkl.load(file)
except:
    c, distances = 0, []
    for i, j in airports_combinations:
        url = 'https://www.prokerala.com/travel/airports/distance/from-' + i.lower() + '/to-' + j.lower() + '/'
        print(url)
        yelp_r = requests.get(url)
        yelp_soup = BeautifulSoup(yelp_r.text, 'html.parser')
        distances.append(str(yelp_soup.findAll(name = 'h2')[0]).split()[3])
        c+=1
        print(c)
    with open('data/distances.pkl', 'wb') as file:
        pkl.dump(distances, file)
In [22]:
distance, c = {}, 0
for i, j in airports_combinations:
    distance[i+j] = float(distances[c])
    distance[j+i] = float(distances[c])
    c+=1

distance_a2a = []
for i in route:
    
    length, dist = len(i)-1, 0
    for j in range(length):
        dist += distance[i[j] + i[j+1]]
    distance_a2a.append(dist)

data['Distance'] = np.array(distance_a2a, dtype = np.float32).reshape((len_train + len_test, 1))

# del airports_combinations, c, dist, distance, distance_a2a, distances, i, j, length, route, url, yelp_r, yelp_soup

Used TF-IDF to get the route feature in a processed way¶
In [24]:
data['Route'] = data['Route'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join(x.split('  ')))

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
tfv = TfidfVectorizer(ngram_range=(1, 1), lowercase=False)
data_route = tfv.fit_transform(data['Route']).toarray()
data_route = pd.DataFrame(data = data_route, columns = tfv.get_feature_names())
data_route.index = data.index
